<div id="content" lang="en" dir="ltr">
Possessors have very low mana (to prevent abuse of the corpse's powers I presume). <p>
This approach prevents the meaningful/frequent use of most spells! 
</p>
<p>
The cost of using a corpse's powers should be a percentage of maxmana, so that the same limits on corpse power use exists yet normal magic use applies for all other skills. 
</p>
<p>
Or perhaps normal mana calculations but a (recharging) marker for corpse powers, say the original corpse casts spells 1 time in 5 it takes 5 turns to recharge the corpse. Whether to allow speed to affect recharging speed or not is an issue to ponder. 
</p>
<p>
<a href="./NeilStevens">NeilStevens</a>: This is known, but I know of nobody who has worked on it. 
</p>
<p>
<a href="./JulesBean">JulesBean</a>: Indeed, this is not a bug, just a game issue.  As in: it's like this by design.  Which is not to say that there might not be some interesting other options available. Feel free to speculate over in the <a href="./IdeaArchive">IdeaArchive</a>. 
</p>
<p>
<a href="./NeilStevens">NeilStevens</a>: You're sure this is by design?  Who desgined it? 
</p>
<p>
<a href="./DarkGod">DarkGod</a>: It is by design, it was first thought by WIlliam Tanskley long time ago. IMO it worked quite well. I'm still pondering if I actaully want to cahnge it or not. More on that latter <img src="./wiki/classic/img/smile.png" alt=":)" height="15" width="15"> 
</p>
<p>
<a href="./NeilStevens">NeilStevens</a>: Well, the monster power system makes sense, but I think it's silly to effectively deny the user access to all his school spells.  Maybe the effects were intended in ToME 1, but in ToME 2 they just don't make any sense at all. 
</p>
